Humbled \xe2\x80\x94 I\xe2\x80\x99ve been awarded a gold GitHub Stars Award by GitHub.

Woah, AH! Cant stop starring at this remarkable thing\xe2\x80\x94the 8th award worldwide out of 60 million developers on GitHub.

It feels great to be recognized for my open-source work, spent over a decade building & helping the FOSS developers community. Thank you, everyone, who made it possible.

\xf0\x9f\x91\x90 Follow me on GitHub:
\xf0\x9f\x8c\x9f Stars Profile:
\xe2\x9c\x8d\xef\xb8\x8f Blog post:

I\xe2\x80\x99ve been creating open-source software for a decade. Joined GitHub on August 4, 2011. I was in college at the time. I remember using GitHub in 2009 but never registered \xe2\x80\x94 no one in the college taught us git.

Ten years later, most of my career direction has been towards building Free & Open Source Software (FOSS). Open-source has brought me many opportunities. It\xe2\x80\x99s helped me connect with a global audience.

Companies like Google, PayPal, Netflix, Microsoft, and Amazon use my code in one way or another. My code (FOSS contributions) runs in almost every WordPress, Node.js, webpack, React, and several other applications \xe2\x80\x94both on earth and Outerspace (via NASA). \xf0\x9f\x9a\x80

I\xe2\x80\x99m always excited to share what I build with others. Thank you for supporting my work. Peace! "

Entrepreneurship isn\xe2\x80\x99t easy: it requires 24X7 dedication that blurs the lines between personal and professional lives at times.

This is not a snap, especially when you are a woman with a young child to take care of.

Often Beating all odds, Women leaders in India of multi-million dollar start ups have proved that they balance it all-work, children,home.

Divya Gokulnath is one such example of a woman who juggles her multiple roles with much success.

In 2011, she co-founded the world\xe2\x80\x99s most valuable ed-tech start-up currently with over 42 million registered students and 3 million annual paid subscriptions.

The start-up is now valued at a whooping $13Bn and is backed by prominent VCs like Tiger Global, General Atlantic, Tencent, and Sequoia Capital.

Divyas net worth today is Rs 1800 cr!!

This is just a tip of the ice-berg, there are a plethora of such examples in India where women are at the pinnacle of an industry, leading their business & family through troughs and peaks.

Can you hear the women roar in the Indian startup society? :) "

An incident happened this past Sunday where a Delhi-based woman replied \xe2\x80\x9cI will kiss my husband. Can you stop me?\xe2\x80\x9d when the policeman asked her and the husband to wear masks.

They were roaming in their car without taking the curfew pass and without wearing the mask.

And that\xe2\x80\x99s how she replies to a person, who\xe2\x80\x99s tasked to ensure our safety.

I don\xe2\x80\x99t understand how insensitive our society has become towards those who\xe2\x80\x99re trying to save our lives.

The healthcare workers and police are putting their lives at risk so that we could remain safe from the virus.

But instead of respecting them, people like her are abusing them.

How is this fair?

I understand the pandemic has stretched too far, and we all want to get back to our normal lives, but that\xe2\x80\x99s not possible right now.

So, why don\xe2\x80\x99t we accept it and do what needs to be done, instead of reacting like her?

Tell me, is staying at home and keeping away from the virus really that bad?

I don\xe2\x80\x99t think so.

The rest of the 25 smaller European countries combined (there are 44 countries in the European continent) - 6 Crores

*Europe - 105.3 + 6 = 111.3 Crores*

Adding the populations of Brazil (21.2 Crores) and Argentina (4.45 Crores)

111.3 Crores + 25.65 Crores = 136.95 Crores


Thus, finally you have arrived at lndias population figure of 136 - 138 Crores.

of stress , anxiety, depression
various health and mental issues.

Bereavement, isolation, loss of income and fear are triggering mental health conditions or exacerbating existing ones.


Many people may be facing increased levels of alcohol and drug use, insomnia, and anxiety.

Meanwhile, COVID-19 itself can
lead to neurological and mental complications, such as delirium, agitation, and stroke. \xf0\x9f\x98\xad\xf0\x9f\x98\xad

People with pre-existing mental, neurological or substance use \xf0\x9f\xa7\x98\xe2\x80\x8d\xe2\x99\x80\xef\xb8\x8f

disorders are also more vulnerable to SARS-CoV-2 infection \xcc\xb6 they may stand a higher risk of severe outcomes .

\xe2\x80\x9cDuring times of crisis, self-care is often difficult to maintain.


Because many of us are busy keeping the fires in our lives from spreading,

we\xe2\x80\x99re usually too fatigued to practice mindful eating, exercise or other refueling activities. \xf0\x9f\xa7\x98\xe2\x80\x8d\xe2\x99\x80\xef\xb8\x8f\xf0\x9f\xa7\x98\xe2\x80\x8d\xe2\x99\x82\xef\xb8\x8f\xf0\x9f\x8e\xba

The pandemic is turning out to be the longest, hardest marathon imaginable. While many countries are looking forward with a degree of optimism, let\xe2\x80\x99s also remember that others are not so fortunate. In India, where many of our teams are based, for example, there were over 272k new cases on Monday and Delhi has now gone into a full lockdown.

These recent surges are clearly putting a strain on local resources, not to mention everyone\xe2\x80\x99s resilience.

My thoughts are with the whole Genpact community and customers working across the world, especially in places that are dealing with new waves of the disease. It goes without saying that we stand with you and encourage everyone to put the health and wellbeing of themselves, their families and communities first.

Coding Blocks, youre awesome!

I posted a query on behalf of my sister, Anamika M., in the early morning. Wasnt expecting anything until the next day, but before I could take my lunch, I got the response and the resolution.

During this interaction I learned that Coding Blocks support team is down with Covid, and we should all wish for their quick recovery, as I do.

Despite that, the haste with which things were settled is not only impressive, but also reenforces the belief in the ethics, the sincerity, and the commitment of the institution towards the development community.

YouTube recommendation engine is just terrible.


At least for me as a user. I am sure it works great from an engagement standpoint

Here is what it seems to do, it keeps recommending content from the same channels, narrow topics or videos over and over again.

You watch one video on a topic/channel/music, it recommends you two more of the same, you watch those and now it is a permanent fixture in your stream.

I or a user ends up engaging because yes it is relevant but it ends up hiding so much other content that YouTube must have.

I have tried deleting my history to update my recommendations but within 3 weeks I have ended up pretty much back to where I was earlier. It feels so stale.

Are there any tools/extensions/approaches to enable better discovery on YouTube?

Finally managed to solve all the problems in a #Google KickStart Round. This has been my best performance till now with a Global Rank of 212 and an India Rank of 71. It felt like a applied almost everything I had learned about Trees, in the past 12 months, in the last problem. Some Dynamic Programming also came to the rescue in the first 2 problems while the 3rd Problem was based on Number Theory and Observations

"Euler Tour on a Tree", "Segment Tree with Lazy Propagation" on the "Flattened tree obtained from the Euler Tour", "Offline Queries" and "GCD" properties.

I know all these terms may seem like jargons but these were the techniques I had to employ to solve the last problem and the feeling after getting that Accepted Verdict on that huge code was just amazing.

To understand this we must learn to differentiate b/w Payment and Settlement network

Let\s say you have an account with bank X while a nearby caf\xc3\xa9 has it with bank Y

When you buy a coffee from your local caf\xc3\xa9 and pay via MasterCard/Visa/UPI, a small value transaction is completed in seconds but it doesn	 mean your accounts are settled

The accounts of both the parties are debited/credited respectively to show correct balances, which certainly doesn	 mean that "money" physically changed hands. This is a \xf0\x9d\x97\xa3\xf0\x9d\x97\xae\xf0\x9d\x98\x86\xf0\x9d\x97\xba\xf0\x9d\x97\xb2\xf0\x9d\x97\xbb\xf0\x9d\x98\x81 \xf0\x9d\x97\xa6\xf0\x9d\x97\xbc\xf0\x9d\x97\xb9\xf0\x9d\x98\x82\xf0\x9d\x98\x81\xf0\x9d\x97\xb6\xf0\x9d\x97\xbc\xf0\x9d\x97\xbb

At the end of the week/month, banks X and Y tally how much does one owe the other for all transactions and then final settlement takes place by physical exchange of money. This is a \xf0\x9d\x97\xa6\xf0\x9d\x97\xb2\xf0\x9d\x98\x81\xf0\x9d\x98\x81\xf0\x9d\x97\xb9\xf0\x9d\x97\xb2\xf0\x9d\x97\xba\xf0\x9d\x97\xb2\xf0\x9d\x97\xbb\xf0\x9d\x98\x81 \xf0\x9d\x97\xa6\xf0\x9d\x97\xbc\xf0\x9d\x97\xb9\xf0\x9d\x98\x82\xf0\x9d\x98\x81\xf0\x9d\x97\xb6\xf0\x9d\x97\xbc\xf0\x9d\x97\xbb

Here, BTC can be used as a settlement mechanism but not payment mechanism. Visa/MasterCard will continue to offer quick payment solutions while final settlement amongst financial institutions will happen in instead of USD

How we schedule our days and how we manage our time is really one of the keys to figuring out how to produce at a very high level. And if there\s one change that I have made in my life, it is incorporating "Batching".

When it comes to some things in life, batching tasks come naturally. We do our laundry once the laundry bag is full. Could you imagine how unproductive our lives could become if we decided to break these type of tasks into 100 different parts? How insane would it be to wash each shirt right after you wore it?

Yet, that\s exactly what we are doing when it comes to many other areas of our lives! When you begin incorporating batching into other domains, you will realize how powerful it can be.

By planning and consolidating tasks, we can prevent constant task switching and focus on the thing that really need to get done. I create batches of time for daily solo tasks, meetings and social activities. These activities require a completely different type of energy, focus and headspace. If I had to switch multiple times between them, it would absolutely drain me.

So, whenever possible, creating batches and using that momentum will really help get things done.

After going through my interview process with Marico Limited I found out I was pregnant. And like most women I wondered what this would mean. Would a company hire someone they know would be going on maternity leave in 7 months. Imagine my surprise when Mehul Bhati Hr calls up not only to congratulate me, but also to say take care of yourself and we will take care of you, when you join us. That call, showed me what it meant to be an employee or rather a member of Marico. Even after I joined, Hr continued to show me this amazing culture. They delayed my induction market visits, so I could go after my first trimester. Even during covid, unlike some companies with a vague directive on whether you should come to office, often leaving employees split between what is expected and a risk of exposure, Marico was clear that safety was first. During this one year, the company has taken so many initiatives like sessions on preventive measures during covid, tie ups for vaccination, tie ups for mental and physical well-being etc. My bar for good culture was high having worked in Coke, but Marico takes it to a new level.

Two years ago, one evening, a team member called me and said, \xe2\x80\x9cToday, we are going to work the whole night.\xe2\x80\x9d He was leading a team of 5-6 people and intended to work overnight to fix a problem.

Here was the problem: Our startup had created thousands of science/math videos but due to some hard-drive damage and process bungling, we were in a mess that the team wanted to sort out.

When I got the call, I told him to sort out the problems during the day. However, my colleague kept persisting. He said, \xe2\x80\x9cThere is too much to do and there isn\xe2\x80\x99t enough time.\xe2\x80\x9d

Finally, since it was already 7:30 pm, I told him, \xe2\x80\x9cWithout my express permission, nobody will stay in the office after 8 pm. Now, pack up and leave right away.\xe2\x80\x9d

The problem was not that we did not have enough time, but that people needed to better understand the process. And at 2 am in the morning, you can\xe2\x80\x99t understand anything -- nobody can.

Unless you are running the fire force, ambulance service, or the police, if you are working at 4 am, there is a 90% chance that you have mismanaged things in the day.

The solution is to use your day thoughtfully instead of running around distractedly, submerged in non-stop emails, meetings, and calls.

Instead of slogging at night, fix your day.

It\xe2\x80\x99s a totally valid question. Theres very little awareness of practical use-cases. We all indirectly use queues, stacks, hashmap, trees, graphs on a daily basis. Even I was fortunate enough to use trees and traversals in one of the projects at Amazon, on a huge scale.

Few good examples:
- Myntra used DynamicProgramming during End of reason sales \xe2\x80\x9918 []
- Uber uses Decision Trees for forecasting demands, fraud detection, ETAs []
- Ubers mobile build system, called SubmitQueue, also utilizes decision trees built on the fly. []
- Skype, Amazon, and UI frameworks extensively use Trees [, ]
- Queue, HashMap, Graphs? Do I really need to give examples for that?

I would insist you all try and explore these underlying things for every single product or feature you use. Once you broaden your views, you will really start loving problem-solving. "

When I had my first bout of DEPRESSION I did not know how to deal with it.

I was failing in whatever I did. It felt like I was travelling in a dark tunnel with no sign of sunlight. I was 21 years & nothing was working in my life. The harder I tried the more I failed. I stopped FIGHTing too hard, things slowly started to change. I came out of it.

My second bout of clinical depression happened a few years later, it was even worse. This time I lost weight, my appetite & felt like giving up. It felt maybe I was slowly dying within. I felt like I was living in a dark room with no windows & no doors. I decided to run away, I took a FLIGHT to a different city. I had a safe landing. The change in context changed everything.

My third bout of clinical depression was bad too. This time I had a sinking heart feeling, I was sulking & brooding. I was unable to come out of it, I tried everything. I was unaware that I was beginning to feel comfortable in darkness. I went to a DOCTOR & told him everything. The doctor gave me pills to eat. Within 2 weeks the medicine worked.

My last bout of depression was 7 years ago, I have come clean:)

I realised the key was empathy to self.
I never loved myself.

Are you loving yourself?
Do you lack empathy for yourself?

Google has a market capital of more than $1.4 Trillion now.

Each day Google receives 3.5 Billion searches which adds up to 1.2 Trillion every year.

But Do you know how Google Search works?
Lets find out in just 4 steps:

1. Crawling - Crawlers like Googlebot look at publicly available webpages and bring data about those webpages back to Googles server.

2. Indexing - Google index includes all info about words & their geographical location.
When we search, at the most basic level, their algorithms look up our search terms in the index to find the appropriate pages.

3. Algorithms- Google uses PageRank Algorithm which rely on more than 200 unique signals including
key terms on website
Freshness of content
Your Region etc.

4. Spam Filter - Google flags the spam sites which tries to be on the top of search results through techniques like repeating keywords over and over, buying links that pass PageRank or putting invisible text on the screen.

& Voila!
Google gives you the information you want in the fastest time possible.

what do you think? what will be the future of search?

Your result will never be directly proportional to the amount of hard work that you have done.

It will be directly proportional to the amount of hard work, your luck, your health at that particular moment and demand.

You may be the best in everything but will not get what you want immediately but if you will keep trying, you will get it definitely.

These are hard times and everyone is putting their efforts to get a good job. The supply is really high and the demand is very less, so don	 get demotivated if you got rejected after doing everything good. Just learn and analyse your mistakes and move on and eventually everything will fall at its place.

You have all the right to be demotivated, lost or cry for some time but do come back to work harder. Interview preparation is not about being enthusiastic all the time. You can feel sometimes that this is not your cup of tea, but at that moment you need to deal it with patience and perseverance.

Every time I open Linkedin, I see professionals from tech/management backgrounds write about how students graduating in the pandemic are incredibly resilient and the pandemic has prepared them for any possible workplace pressure and why they would make fantastic assets to the organization. To be really frank, this romanticization of struggle and pain is just so upsetting. Students graduating in 2020 and 2021 are anxious, depressed, incredibly stressed, dealing with isolation and persisting uncertainty. We are literally hanging by a thread. People who can, ought to be hiring/helping/mentoring graduating batches because its the kind and responsible thing to do during a global pandemic - not to derive some utility from them and capitalise on struggle.\n\nEdit : Didnt expect such an overwhelming response, for so many people to resonate with what I thought was a personal frustration. However, as terrible as our situation is, even to be in higher education or sitting for interviews is a privilege at this point in India. While youre here, would urge you to take a look at Anubhutis work in Maharashtra especially aimed at helping disfranchised who are ineligible for goverment support during these precarious times. "

"Optimize for a workplace with great work life balance".
This is such a double-edged advice to a young professional. Most great engineers I see around myself, went all out building skills when they entered their first job.
I myself worked 12+ hours per day in my first job, and slowly I came to a stage where I had to work less than 4-5 hours getting my work done (because I got better at doing my work).

I know I am going to get some social media flak for this, but this is important to be called out. If work life balance is important to you, learn and earn work life balance. Your career is a 40 year long journey. Don	 start optimising too early.

If you die tomorrow, your job will be filled next week.

So learn to log off.

Spend some time with loved ones.

Spend some time doing that thing you wanted to do.

Youre replaceable to the employer, but youre irreplaceable to the people that matter.

Life is a commodity.

Spend it wisely. "

I have finally drawn the courage to share my topsy-turvy ride from non-Tier 1 (IIT/NIT) college where I did not get any good internship, to securing a job offer at Google.

In my college, I was in ECE (Electronics). In the first year, I discovered that I dont have any interest in ECE. I decided to work hard and get my branch changed to CSE.

Second year - I was a newbie in programming. I didnt know how to code in any language when people around me were 4-6* on CodeChef. I learnt Java, but did not explore programming much.
So I started reading history/geography books thinking that maybe engineering is not my thing and that I should look for alternatives.

Third year - there was a subject called Design and Analysis of Algorithms in which I got interested. I finally decided to explore this field.

By the final year, I practiced a lot of interview problems from Geeks and LeetCode.

I cracked and now . \xf0\x9f\x98\x80

In short, I discovered that I was afraid to pursue my dreams due to my fear of being late at it and seeing the competition around me.

But in the journey I learnt that it takes courage and a lot of hard work to pursue dreams
Life gives you opportunity at every stage, its just about when you are ready to grab them.

Dreams do come true \xf0\x9f\x98\x80 "

Dr. Rajagopalan & team at IIT Madras have found a way to digitally restore blurry and indistinct pics, affected by rain, motion, haze, etc. Their Image Processing & Computer Vision Lab is using artificial neural networks to restore degraded images.
\xe2\x80\x9cWe have developed a deep learning network that decomposes the restoration task into two stages: degradation localization and degraded region-guided restoration. Our premise is to use the auxiliary task of degradation mask prediction to guide the restoration process. We demonstrate that solving this auxiliary task injects crucial localizing ability in network layers. We transfer this ability to the main restoration network using attentive knowledge-distillation and focus on the refinement of degraded regions by exploiting this additional knowledge,\xe2\x80\x9d explains Dr. Rajagopalan.

Recruiter: Whats your current CTC?
Sahaj: \xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x80\x94Silence\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x80\x94

Recruiter: Sahaj?
Sahaj: Why do you want to know my current CTC?

Recruiter: I want to check if you are in our salary range.
: Well, What\xe2\x80\x99s your budget?, Ill tell you if I fit there.

Recruiter: Sahaj you know, its part of the interview.
: That\xe2\x80\x99s why I am saying I\xe2\x80\x99ll tell you my expectation and you tell me If that is in the range?

Recruiter: You know you will have to share your salary slips in Background verification!
: Ok but why my current salary is so important?

Recruiter: Uhhh\xe2\x80\xa6..
: Just say, so you can pay me 10-15% more than that!

Hung up.

Something that should never happen is a daily routine in our industry and people are struggling.

Example -

I created a resume for my client, It worked, He got calls from all big4 and consulting firms, got 3 offer letters as well but he had to reject all 3 because The CTC is really low and he knows that he will struggle in the future if he says Yes.

P.S - Recruiter, HR is not to be blamed for this!

USA and UK have a Salary history ban law and It\xe2\x80\x99s time that we also stop judging people on the last CTC.

Let me know if you support this or if it happened to you! "

I didn	 know how to use a sanitary napkin, but I learned it for my daughter.

I often say, "Motherhood is a behavior!"

Being a transgender woman, I never experienced periods. But with Gayatri (my adopted daughter), I was raising a girl child.

I teach all my kids (at Aaji Cha Ghar) about good touch and bad touch.

When Gayatri reached her teens and her periods approached, she started feeling uncomfortable with me.

I was blank!

As any biological mother or woman who raises a girl child, I had to teach my daughter about vaginal fluids, periods, and other biological changes in the body.

I learned it all for Gayatri. She truly brought out the mother in me.

Why I am sharing all this?

Because transgenders are humans too! Like any other male or female that evolves as a parent and learns the process on the go, I and many others like me, are learning too.

We too want to live a normal life but the decades of discrimination, disrespect, fear, abandonment, and what not have made it difficult for us to lead one.

My only request to you would be - treat the transgenders as HUMANS!

Very few people know that getting into the IITs was a dream for me.
I tried during my 12th.
Didn	 make it. Not even close.

It was the first time I saw my father cry.
I am guessing he felt this would be what will get us out of our financial miseries.
I don	 know. I never asked him why he cried that day.

I didn	 make it to any engineering college. None that mattered, that I wanted to get into.

So I decided to go for a 3-yr B. Sc degree from St. Stephens.
I was rejected at the interview stage.
Dr. Wilson said, "I don	 think you will be good in Physics"

Tried again for the IITs while in 1st year of college.
Didn	 make it. Not even close.

This time no one cried. Not even me.
Maybe I knew it all along.

As on date, it is easy for someone to assume that where I ended up in life (colleges, companies, investors, etc.) were not my first choices and hence are not the right choices. Except that is not true.

I was rejected by everyone. But they accepted me. They are no less in my eyes. Never!

It\s just that I\m insanely lucky. So lucky that it shocks me at times.

My success remains unexplained.
I cannot justify it nor can claim it.

Heres a simplified timeline for those applying to Masters Programs for Fall 2022 from Gradvine

1. Start GRE prep by March/April. Give the first attempt by May-June. The number of attempts does not matter. Always leave room for multiple attempts.

2. University selection: Have an idea about universities to target before the GRE itself. GRE shouldnt fully dictate your university choice.

3. Have your final GRE score by August 2021 latest. Finish GRE before starting application documents.
Juggling GRE+college/work+applications gets taxing

4. Start your SOP: Solid application documents take 45-60 days to prepare. Start working on them by mid-August latest.

5. TOEFL/IELTS: Finish your TOEFL/IELTS in the months of August-September. Straightforward exams so this can be done in parallel to application completion.

6. Submit your Application: Submit your application early to improve chances. Not later than November 2021.

7. Expect University decisions by January-April-2022.

8. Secure your loans by May 2022 & appear for visa interview by June-July-2022.


No one has ever regretted starting early! The time you lose will never come back. While Ive given you milestones, these are the latest dates by which you should ideally get things done. Starting early makes the process easier. "

My IIT-JEE rank was in the 3000s. This got me branches I hadn	 heard of before. Between deep sea drilling engineering in Kharagpur 3000 kilometers away from home and Computer Science in NIT Calicut literally 20 minutes down the road, I picked up the latter.

But in my head, it was a step down. I (stupidly) wanted the IIT tag. So, I was never happy at NITC. In 4 years, I came out not learning much.

For many of my friends though, NITC was an achievement. They were happy to be there and wanted to learn. They made the best of the opportunities they got. Eventually, they did well, became great developers, and some went to places like Stanford. Some of my friends in NIT did far better in life than my \xe2\x80\x9cimaginary\xe2\x80\x9d IIT self.

If you are a startup, it is tempting to hire from IITs and IIMs. But then, they may want to be in Google or a Goldman. Ask yourself, are you what these guys aspire to be in? If not, consider hiring the guys who are happy to join you, like what you do, who want to learn, and are motivated to do well with what they got. This will pay off massively.



PS: Some of the best engineers in our team are from relatively obscure colleges.

PS2: While making a JD, please consider removing that "Must be from Tier-1/Tier-2 college" line. It is unnecessary elitism.

YouTube recommendation engine is just terrible.


At least for me as a user. I am sure it works great from an engagement standpoint

Here is what it seems to do, it keeps recommending content from the same channels, narrow topics or videos over and over again.

You watch one video on a topic/channel/music, it recommends you two more of the same, you watch those and now it is a permanent fixture in your stream.

I or a user ends up engaging because yes it is relevant but it ends up hiding so much other content that YouTube must have.

I have tried deleting my history to update my recommendations but within 3 weeks I have ended up pretty much back to where I was earlier. It feels so stale.

Are there any tools/extensions/approaches to enable better discovery on YouTube?

To understand this we must learn to differentiate b/w Payment and Settlement network

Let\s say you have an account with bank X while a nearby caf\xc3\xa9 has it with bank Y

When you buy a coffee from your local caf\xc3\xa9 and pay via MasterCard/Visa/UPI, a small value transaction is completed in seconds but it doesn	 mean your accounts are settled

The accounts of both the parties are debited/credited respectively to show correct balances, which certainly doesn	 mean that "money" physically changed hands. This is a \xf0\x9d\x97\xa3\xf0\x9d\x97\xae\xf0\x9d\x98\x86\xf0\x9d\x97\xba\xf0\x9d\x97\xb2\xf0\x9d\x97\xbb\xf0\x9d\x98\x81 \xf0\x9d\x97\xa6\xf0\x9d\x97\xbc\xf0\x9d\x97\xb9\xf0\x9d\x98\x82\xf0\x9d\x98\x81\xf0\x9d\x97\xb6\xf0\x9d\x97\xbc\xf0\x9d\x97\xbb

At the end of the week/month, banks X and Y tally how much does one owe the other for all transactions and then final settlement takes place by physical exchange of money. This is a \xf0\x9d\x97\xa6\xf0\x9d\x97\xb2\xf0\x9d\x98\x81\xf0\x9d\x98\x81\xf0\x9d\x97\xb9\xf0\x9d\x97\xb2\xf0\x9d\x97\xba\xf0\x9d\x97\xb2\xf0\x9d\x97\xbb\xf0\x9d\x98\x81 \xf0\x9d\x97\xa6\xf0\x9d\x97\xbc\xf0\x9d\x97\xb9\xf0\x9d\x98\x82\xf0\x9d\x98\x81\xf0\x9d\x97\xb6\xf0\x9d\x97\xbc\xf0\x9d\x97\xbb

How we schedule our days and how we manage our time is really one of the keys to figuring out how to produce at a very high level. And if there\s one change that I have made in my life, it is incorporating "Batching".

When it comes to some things in life, batching tasks come naturally. We do our laundry once the laundry bag is full. Could you imagine how unproductive our lives could become if we decided to break these type of tasks into 100 different parts? How insane would it be to wash each shirt right after you wore it?

Yet, that\s exactly what we are doing when it comes to many other areas of our lives! When you begin incorporating batching into other domains, you will realize how powerful it can be.

By planning and consolidating tasks, we can prevent constant task switching and focus on the thing that really need to get done. I create batches of time for daily solo tasks, meetings and social activities. These activities require a completely different type of energy, focus and headspace. If I had to switch multiple times between them, it would absolutely drain me.

So, whenever possible, creating batches and using that momentum will really help get things done.

After going through my interview process with Marico Limited I found out I was pregnant. And like most women I wondered what this would mean. Would a company hire someone they know would be going on maternity leave in 7 months. Imagine my surprise when Mehul Bhati Hr calls up not only to congratulate me, but also to say take care of yourself and we will take care of you, when you join us. That call, showed me what it meant to be an employee or rather a member of Marico. Even after I joined, Hr continued to show me this amazing culture. They delayed my induction market visits, so I could go after my first trimester. Even during covid, unlike some companies with a vague directive on whether you should come to office, often leaving employees split between what is expected and a risk of exposure, Marico was clear that safety was first. During this one year, the company has taken so many initiatives like sessions on preventive measures during covid, tie ups for vaccination, tie ups for mental and physical well-being etc. My bar for good culture was high having worked in Coke, but Marico takes it to a new level.

Very few people know that getting into the IITs was a dream for me.
I tried during my 12th.
Didn	 make it. Not even close.

It was the first time I saw my father cry.
I am guessing he felt this would be what will get us out of our financial miseries.
I don	 know. I never asked him why he cried that day.

I didn	 make it to any engineering college. None that mattered, that I wanted to get into.

So I decided to go for a 3-yr B. Sc degree from St. Stephens.
I was rejected at the interview stage.
Dr. Wilson said, "I don	 think you will be good in Physics"

Tried again for the IITs while in 1st year of college.
Didn	 make it. Not even close.

This time no one cried. Not even me.
Maybe I knew it all along.

As on date, it is easy for someone to assume that where I ended up in life (colleges, companies, investors, etc.) were not my first choices and hence are not the right choices. Except that is not true.

I was rejected by everyone. But they accepted me. They are no less in my eyes. Never!

It\s just that I\m insanely lucky. So lucky that it shocks me at times.

My success remains unexplained.
I cannot justify it nor can claim it.

Heres a simplified timeline for those applying to Masters Programs for Fall 2022 from Gradvine

1. Start GRE prep by March/April. Give the first attempt by May-June. The number of attempts does not matter. Always leave room for multiple attempts.

2. University selection: Have an idea about universities to target before the GRE itself. GRE shouldnt fully dictate your university choice.

3. Have your final GRE score by August 2021 latest. Finish GRE before starting application documents.
Juggling GRE+college/work+applications gets taxing

4. Start your SOP: Solid application documents take 45-60 days to prepare. Start working on them by mid-August latest.

5. TOEFL/IELTS: Finish your TOEFL/IELTS in the months of August-September. Straightforward exams so this can be done in parallel to application completion.

6. Submit your Application: Submit your application early to improve chances. Not later than November 2021.

7. Expect University decisions by January-April-2022.

8. Secure your loans by May 2022 & appear for visa interview by June-July-2022.


No one has ever regretted starting early! The time you lose will never come back. While Ive given you milestones, these are the latest dates by which you should ideally get things done. Starting early makes the process easier. "

Two years ago, one evening, a team member called me and said, \xe2\x80\x9cToday, we are going to work the whole night.\xe2\x80\x9d He was leading a team of 5-6 people and intended to work overnight to fix a problem.

Here was the problem: Our startup had created thousands of science/math videos but due to some hard-drive damage and process bungling, we were in a mess that the team wanted to sort out.

When I got the call, I told him to sort out the problems during the day. However, my colleague kept persisting. He said, \xe2\x80\x9cThere is too much to do and there isn\xe2\x80\x99t enough time.\xe2\x80\x9d

Finally, since it was already 7:30 pm, I told him, \xe2\x80\x9cWithout my express permission, nobody will stay in the office after 8 pm. Now, pack up and leave right away.\xe2\x80\x9d

The problem was not that we did not have enough time, but that people needed to better understand the process. And at 2 am in the morning, you can\xe2\x80\x99t understand anything -- nobody can.

Unless you are running the fire force, ambulance service, or the police, if you are working at 4 am, there is a 90% chance that you have mismanaged things in the day.

The solution is to use your day thoughtfully instead of running around distractedly, submerged in non-stop emails, meetings, and calls.

Instead of slogging at night, fix your day.

Google has a market capital of more than $1.4 Trillion now.

Each day Google receives 3.5 Billion searches which adds up to 1.2 Trillion every year.

But Do you know how Google Search works?
Lets find out in just 4 steps:

1. Crawling - Crawlers like Googlebot look at publicly available webpages and bring data about those webpages back to Googles server.

2. Indexing - Google index includes all info about words & their geographical location.
When we search, at the most basic level, their algorithms look up our search terms in the index to find the appropriate pages.

3. Algorithms- Google uses PageRank Algorithm which rely on more than 200 unique signals including
key terms on website
Freshness of content
Your Region etc.

4. Spam Filter - Google flags the spam sites which tries to be on the top of search results through techniques like repeating keywords over and over, buying links that pass PageRank or putting invisible text on the screen.

& Voila!
Google gives you the information you want in the fastest time possible.

what do you think? what will be the future of search?

My IIT-JEE rank was in the 3000s. This got me branches I hadn	 heard of before. Between deep sea drilling engineering in Kharagpur 3000 kilometers away from home and Computer Science in NIT Calicut literally 20 minutes down the road, I picked up the latter.

But in my head, it was a step down. I (stupidly) wanted the IIT tag. So, I was never happy at NITC. In 4 years, I came out not learning much.

For many of my friends though, NITC was an achievement. They were happy to be there and wanted to learn. They made the best of the opportunities they got. Eventually, they did well, became great developers, and some went to places like Stanford. Some of my friends in NIT did far better in life than my \xe2\x80\x9cimaginary\xe2\x80\x9d IIT self.

If you are a startup, it is tempting to hire from IITs and IIMs. But then, they may want to be in Google or a Goldman. Ask yourself, are you what these guys aspire to be in? If not, consider hiring the guys who are happy to join you, like what you do, who want to learn, and are motivated to do well with what they got. This will pay off massively.



PS: Some of the best engineers in our team are from relatively obscure colleges.

PS2: While making a JD, please consider removing that "Must be from Tier-1/Tier-2 college" line. It is unnecessary elitism.

This is one of my older posts, Its almost a year now. Time flies..

Around 4 years ago I also used to visit LinkedIn.com and scroll through the feeds and everyone seemed to be so happy, sharing their news about selection in companies like Amazon, Facebook, Google, Cool Startups, Microsoft, Service based firms etc.

There were also some set of people talking about their achievements in Masters from reputed institution, Code Challenges, Innovation and much more.

I used to see title below the names of people and then used to peek into their profile to know about their journey. Literally I felt so down, always used to compare myself with them.

Now after 4 years I feel like there was no difference at all, its just that the nights I was sleeping they were awake working hard, and I knew I was late so when they were sleeping I was awake working hard...

So yeah, never feel you are different or incapable, just a spark is all you need ! !

:)

Your result will never be directly proportional to the amount of hard work that you have done.

It will be directly proportional to the amount of hard work, your luck, your health at that particular moment and demand.

You may be the best in everything but will not get what you want immediately but if you will keep trying, you will get it definitely.

These are hard times and everyone is putting their efforts to get a good job. The supply is really high and the demand is very less, so don	 get demotivated if you got rejected after doing everything good. Just learn and analyse your mistakes and move on and eventually everything will fall at its place.

You have all the right to be demotivated, lost or cry for some time but do come back to work harder. Interview preparation is not about being enthusiastic all the time. You can feel sometimes that this is not your cup of tea, but at that moment you need to deal it with patience and perseverance.

"Success is nothing but another chapter of failure."

"Optimize for a workplace with great work life balance".
This is such a double-edged advice to a young professional. Most great engineers I see around myself, went all out building skills when they entered their first job.
I myself worked 12+ hours per day in my first job, and slowly I came to a stage where I had to work less than 4-5 hours getting my work done (because I got better at doing my work).

I know I am going to get some social media flak for this, but this is important to be called out. If work life balance is important to you, learn and earn work life balance. Your career is a 40 year long journey. Don	 start optimising too early.

There Are No #Failures in Life, Only Growth Lessons

Brian Acton the founder of WhatsApp
Rejected by Facebook
Rejected by Twitter

Comes Sooner or Later
We should keep trying and never give-up

Without his failure to integrate Facebook in 2009, Brian Acton would probably never have created WhatsApp. He would have been a great programmer at Facebook but would have been one among the thousands of other programmers.

His failure allowed him to build something even bigger.

It all started with the way he reacted to that failure. Instead of feeling sorry for himself and blaming himself, Brian Acton chose to take action. This is the essential key you must have in mind. \xf0\x9f\x92\xa1 \xf0\x9f\x92\xa1 \xf0\x9f\x92\xa1

I have finally drawn the courage to share my topsy-turvy ride from non-Tier 1 (IIT/NIT) college where I did not get any good internship, to securing a job offer at Google.

In my college, I was in ECE (Electronics). In the first year, I discovered that I dont have any interest in ECE. I decided to work hard and get my branch changed to CSE.

Second year - I was a newbie in programming. I didnt know how to code in any language when people around me were 4-6* on CodeChef. I learnt Java, but did not explore programming much.
So I started reading history/geography books thinking that maybe engineering is not my thing and that I should look for alternatives.

Third year - there was a subject called Design and Analysis of Algorithms in which I got interested. I finally decided to explore this field.

By the final year, I practiced a lot of interview problems from Geeks and LeetCode.

I cracked and now . \xf0\x9f\x98\x80

In short, I discovered that I was afraid to pursue my dreams due to my fear of being late at it and seeing the competition around me.

But in the journey I learnt that it takes courage and a lot of hard work to pursue dreams
Life gives you opportunity at every stage, its just about when you are ready to grab them.

Dreams do come true \xf0\x9f\x98\x80 "

I didn	 know how to use a sanitary napkin, but I learned it for my daughter.

I often say, "Motherhood is a behavior!"

Being a transgender woman, I never experienced periods. But with Gayatri (my adopted daughter), I was raising a girl child.

I teach all my kids (at Aaji Cha Ghar) about good touch and bad touch.

When Gayatri reached her teens and her periods approached, she started feeling uncomfortable with me.

I was blank!

As any biological mother or woman who raises a girl child, I had to teach my daughter about vaginal fluids, periods, and other biological changes in the body.

I learned it all for Gayatri. She truly brought out the mother in me.

Why I am sharing all this?

Because transgenders are humans too! Like any other male or female that evolves as a parent and learns the process on the go, I and many others like me, are learning too.

We too want to live a normal life but the decades of discrimination, disrespect, fear, abandonment, and what not have made it difficult for us to lead one.

My only request to you would be - treat the transgenders as HUMANS!

Yes, Im tired too

Tired of being locked in, in my 20s

Frustrated at not being able to live life to the fullest.

Angry at the world I cannot explore,

Grieved by the toll its taking on my relationships.

But perhaps,
Not as tired as health workers sweating in 16 hour shifts.
Not as frustrated as the girl, whos trying to desperately find a source of remdesivir, or the guy begging for plasma for their parents, who are critical.
Not as angry, as the stall owner who goes to sleep hungry every day the curfew extends.
Not as Grieved, as those standing in 8 hour queues, to perform the last rites of their dead, with dignity.

So while I understand, that there are many of you, who are in the same boat as me, please think about those right now, who have it worse. And let us all help each other get through this. "

So, the main thing to note in Modi Ji\s announcement is "We have to save India from Lockdown".

On one hand, I totally agree with him. There are a lot of cons of lockdown rather than pros. Some of them are :-

\xe2\x80\xa2 The first and the major is Education sector. The students of class 1st to 5th have got phones and they are using it to watch and play games. Class 6th to 11th students are busy in making accounts and becoming influencers. 12th class students are going through tough times to prepare bcoz coaching are online and online is not that effective as offline. Only some College students are utilising their time online.

\xe2\x80\xa2 The second is Daily Wage workers. They really go through a bad time during lockdown.

\xe2\x80\xa2 The third is economy and unemployment. The number of persons that become unemployment is beyond our thoughts.

There are many other reasons as well. On the other hand, only bcoz of one reason that people are dying bcoz of Covid, I want everyone to stay at home safely with their families.

If I missed anything or not seeing the big picture, do add your opinion in the comment section.

Stay safe, stay healthy.

0 Interviews and Development in real-life are totally different."

For example, consider a JavaScript code -
1 + 2 + " apples " + [1, 2, 3]

Case 1) In Interviews:
What would be the output of above line?
A) 3 apples 1,2,3
B) 3 apples [1,2,3]
C) 12 apples 1,2,3
D) 12 apples [1, 2, 3]

If you are not able to answer this, you will be judged on your "type coersion" knowledge in JavaScript.

Case 2) In Real-Life Software Engineering:
If the same line is seen in a code review, you will get a comment -

"This looks confusing - what the final output of this line would be?
Either break this down in a more readable and predictable manner OR write how the output would look like as a comment above this line."

BTW, what do you think is the output? Comment below.
